00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:28.379
What I say in my book is that all of this
material and research for the past five years

00:08:28.379 --> 00:08:35.469
is like one giant, really, really big rich
pilot study.

00:08:35.469 --> 00:08:38.219
This is what I see at my end.

00:08:38.219 --> 00:08:44.490
And this is the color representation of what's
going on in the brain in real-time.

00:08:44.490 --> 00:08:50.209
So, I'm using a technology called EEG, or
electroencephalogram.

00:08:50.209 --> 00:08:55.510
And it divides up the brain here into various
regions that roughly match where there are

00:08:55.510 --> 00:08:57.290
different lobes and fissures in the brain.

00:08:57.290 --> 00:09:00.420
So, it isn't completely arbitrary mapping.

00:09:00.420 --> 00:09:03.230
And I see this nice color representation.

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:04.560
And it's more than color.

00:09:04.560 --> 00:09:06.970
There's actually two pieces of information.

00:09:06.970 --> 00:09:09.260
There's the color, which indicates frequency.

00:09:09.260 --> 00:09:13.019
And then, there's the length of the bar here,
which indicates amplitude.

00:09:13.019 --> 00:09:16.281
So, after I spend two or three hours with
the student there may actually be something

00:09:16.281 --> 00:09:20.340
like 60 megabytes worth of data on their brain
activities.

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:21.529
So, that's a statistician’s nightmare.

00:09:21.529 --> 00:09:23.990
And fortunately, I'm not a statistician.

00:09:23.990 --> 00:09:28.490
So I don't have to deal with all of that.

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:30.441
And so, that's a little bit of what I see
from my end.

00:09:30.441 --> 00:09:32.380
And it does change in real-time.

00:09:32.380 --> 00:09:41.190
But the really funny thing is the brain activity
comes about 300 milliseconds before the person

00:09:41.190 --> 00:09:45.330
executes the action or behavior associated
with the brain activity.

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:49.779
So, as I'm watching--and you would see it,
too--you would actually see something light

00:09:49.779 --> 00:09:54.079
up in the brain and think for a moment, "Oh,
the person's about to do such and such."

00:09:54.079 --> 00:09:57.830
But by the time that thought occurs to you,
they've already gone ahead and done it.

00:09:57.830 --> 00:10:02.310
So, it's a little bit like mind reading, but
there's such a short period of time, that

00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:04.519
mind-reading is not that helpful.

00:10:04.519 --> 00:10:08.399
There's no time to take notes or anything
like that, or even say anything.

00:10:08.399 --> 00:10:12.920
It's just enough time for it to register in
my brain, which coincidentally between perception

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:17.160
and the thought, the matching is also about
the same amount of time.

00:10:17.160 --> 00:10:21.620
So, it's a really wonderful, very quick--.

00:10:21.620 --> 00:10:26.399
When they're doing mathematics for example,
and they're going to carry the one, you can

00:10:26.399 --> 00:10:29.480
see that 'cause the brain does something.

00:10:29.480 --> 00:10:34.750
So, to summarize what it is that I'm working
with here, electroencephalogram, and it's

00:10:34.750 --> 00:10:36.959
measuring activity in the neocortex only.

00:10:36.959 --> 00:10:40.310
So, there are different layers of the brain
and this is the outer layer.

00:10:40.310 --> 00:10:42.470
Really, really important in human beings.

00:10:42.470 --> 00:10:48.040
Our neocortex is huge compared to even the
other great apes and certainly monkeys on

00:10:48.040 --> 00:10:51.899
down to very, very small neocortex compared
to what we have.

00:10:51.899 --> 00:10:52.899
It's fast.

00:10:52.899 --> 00:10:53.899
It's simple.

00:10:53.899 --> 00:10:54.910
It's cheap.

00:10:54.910 --> 00:11:00.690
Contrary to what people might think, professors
are paid terribly and we very little funding

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:03.250
except for the few who somehow manage to wrangle
up something.

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:09.420
So, it's great to some research that doesn't
cost ten or twenty thousand a student.

00:11:09.420 --> 00:11:11.670
The different colors.

00:11:11.670 --> 00:11:12.670
Know that red--.

00:11:12.670 --> 00:11:16.949
It follows the color spectrum, so red indicates
that that region is showing the most activity

00:11:16.949 --> 00:11:18.620
there.

00:11:18.620 --> 00:11:22.630
And if we go down then from yellow, that's
a little bit less.

00:11:22.630 --> 00:11:25.540
Green, less still, but on the low end.

00:11:25.540 --> 00:11:26.779
Blue, much less.

00:11:26.779 --> 00:11:29.740
That's a relaxed state.

00:11:29.740 --> 00:11:35.319
If the brain were all blue, that would indicate
you're on the edge of sleep.

00:11:35.319 --> 00:11:38.930
You might even be aware, but you're not active
in any way.

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:41.300
And then black indicates no activity.

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:45.589
And yes, something that's really interesting
is most people have one or two regions, even

00:11:45.589 --> 00:11:51.190
after I go through and calibrate and whatnot,
one or two regions that simply show no activity

00:11:51.190 --> 00:11:53.900
except under the greatest duress or stimulus.

00:11:53.900 --> 00:11:58.509
So, as we go through the different regions,
I mentioned those, you might consider which

00:11:58.509 --> 00:12:05.140
