First impressions are very important.

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:39.850
And so, be careful about what you say on your
first date.

00:14:39.850 --> 00:14:42.660
No sex, no politics, no religion, no death.

00:14:42.660 --> 00:14:44.259
And you'll be good.

00:14:44.259 --> 00:14:49.920
So, they also do simulated speed dating and
they do a role play with actors.

00:14:49.920 --> 00:14:57.730
A couple of ENFP theater students have come
in concocted a variety of situations.

00:14:57.730 --> 00:14:58.899
Recalling items on a list.

00:14:58.899 --> 00:15:00.819
Details in a scene.

00:15:00.819 --> 00:15:04.749
And then some open-ended stuff, like go back
to your childhood, or foresee into the future

00:15:04.749 --> 00:15:08.149
or where is your life gonna be ten years from
now.

00:15:08.149 --> 00:15:14.740
And we might think with something like this,
maybe its memory.

00:15:14.740 --> 00:15:18.490
So, recall an event from your childhood that
maybe there will be visualization and a little

00:15:18.490 --> 00:15:19.589
bit of memory regions.

00:15:19.589 --> 00:15:24.250
But there are some individuals who stand out
as recalling information in a very special

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:25.250
way.

00:15:25.250 --> 00:15:28.570
And some individuals who visualize the future
in a very special way.

00:15:28.570 --> 00:15:32.970
So, all of them have this potential to show
individual differences.

00:15:32.970 --> 00:15:34.550
And, oops.

00:15:34.550 --> 00:15:35.550
There we go.

00:15:35.550 --> 00:15:38.759
So this is an example of an easy open-ended
task.

00:15:38.759 --> 00:15:40.410
What comes to mind?

00:15:40.410 --> 00:15:45.070
And a lot of folks will mention stories as
we go along.

00:15:45.070 --> 00:15:47.970
Maybe what are some possible interpretations
of the story?

00:15:47.970 --> 00:15:52.180
Something telling is how many different interpretations
can a person give.

00:15:52.180 --> 00:15:55.610
Some folks are like, "Well, there's one and
maybe two."

00:15:55.610 --> 00:15:57.279
And then they peter out.

00:15:57.279 --> 00:16:02.029
And others can continue on for a while and
be able to offer different scenarios.

00:16:02.029 --> 00:16:06.240
I mean, perhaps she's upset because she's
just poisoned him.

00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:08.069
And there's a whole bunch of things you could
read into it.

00:16:08.069 --> 00:16:11.129
And then, they think the task is over, but
it's not.

00:16:11.129 --> 00:16:13.579
Fifteen minutes later, we come back to it.

00:16:13.579 --> 00:16:14.960
I don't show them the picture, though.

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:18.170
I just say, "Remember that picture I showed
you?

00:16:18.170 --> 00:16:21.759
Could you recall for me as many details as
you can?"

00:16:21.759 --> 00:16:23.009
And so, they remember the details.

00:16:23.009 --> 00:16:26.029
And the things they don't mention, I’ll
say something like, "Does the dress go down

00:16:26.029 --> 00:16:28.670
to her ankles, to her knees?

00:16:28.670 --> 00:16:30.580
Does it cover her feet?"

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:31.959
All that kind of stuff.

00:16:31.959 --> 00:16:33.499
And really is amazing.

00:16:33.499 --> 00:16:37.069
It's very consistent with personality type
who remembers more.

00:16:37.069 --> 00:16:40.339
In fact, it's great because there are--.

00:16:40.339 --> 00:16:46.139
One type, all of the ENFJ and ENTJ, if we
have any of those in the room.

00:16:46.139 --> 00:16:50.790
Those two personality types actually remember
a lot of details, but incorrectly.

00:16:50.790 --> 00:16:51.790
[laughter]

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:54.120
So, it's important to know.

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:57.540
Otherwise, the SP types are the ones who actually
remember the most.

00:16:57.540 --> 00:17:01.800
And which I found maybe people thought that
was a little bit of a surprise, but I think

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:06.530
because there's a drama in the image they
remember it.

00:17:06.530 --> 00:17:09.740
So, what I found overall.

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:15.089
One is there are these regions of the neocortex
that light up when they're being used for

00:17:15.089 --> 00:17:16.440
an activity.

00:17:16.440 --> 00:17:22.000
And really, each region has what is called
the "threshold to activation."

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:27.101
That if you receive just a little bit of input
and it doesn't pass that threshold, the region

00:17:27.101 --> 00:17:28.390
doesn't light up at all.

00:17:28.390 --> 00:17:32.650
But the moment you pass the threshold, then
it begins to light up.

00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:35.150
For some folks, that threshold is very low.

00:17:35.150 --> 00:17:39.260
So, almost any kind of stimulus will light
it up and the more stimulus they get, the

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:40.490
more it gets active.

00:17:40.490 --> 00:17:46.300
For other folks the level, the activation
to, the threshold activation is much higher.

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:50.470
So that there's a lot of input that will come
in and it doesn't get active, doesn't light

00:17:50.470 --> 00:17:54.270
up, and then all of a sudden it would be really,
really active out of nowhere.

00:17:54.270 --> 00:17:56.280
So, this region actually is related to embarrassment.

00:17:56.280 --> 00:17:59.730
Now, all of us love to be embarrassed, right?

00:17:59.730 --> 00:18:03.260
[audience chuckles]
Some of us more easily embarrass than others.

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:09.330
So, ENFJs for example, the personality type,
are really pretty easy to embarrass.

00:18:09.330 --> 00:18:10.610
And in fact, you can point out, "Oh, look.

00:18:10.610 --> 00:18:12.250
The embarrassment region is lighting up."

00:18:12.250 --> 00:18:14.490
And then they get more embarrassed.

00:18:14.490 --> 00:18:15.490
And then, "Oh, look.

00:18:15.490 --> 00:18:16.990
You're getting even more embarrassed."

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:20.540
And then it lights up even more.

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:25.880
And other folks very, very difficult to activate.

00:18:25.880 --> 00:18:32.550
But INTPs, so those are very different folks,
generally speaking, that region is quite dark.

00:18:32.550 --> 00:18:37.780
They don't even notice the social feedbacks,
so why would they get embarrassed?

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:42.430
But when they do get embarrassed, oh boy,
does that activate.

00:18:42.430 --> 00:18:43.430
Not just in that region.

00:18:43.430 --> 00:18:48.300
It floods over like a little tsunami to all
of the neighboring regions as well.

00:18:48.300 --> 00:18:52.810
And so, it's funny because one of the neighboring
regions to this area here is the one responsible

00:18:52.810 --> 00:18:57.840
for dexterity and for moving smoothly in the
environment and having boundaries between

00:18:57.840 --> 00:18:59.020
self and others.

00:18:59.020 --> 00:19:03.030
So, if you've ever known someone who doesn't
get embarrassed very often, but when they

00:19:03.030 --> 00:19:08.990
do, all of a sudden becomes flushed red and
they're klutzy and that's those folks there.

00:19:08.990 --> 00:19:12.440
So, that's representing how the brain works.

00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:19.860
And dark regions indicate what's not in use
has really become automatic.

00:19:19.860 --> 00:19:23.920
Signing your name should be a pretty easy,
mindless experience.

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:28.820
There are various, also, holistic patterns
for the whole brain.

00:19:28.820 --> 00:19:30.160
And there are zigzag sequences.

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:33.300
And so, we'll take a look at some of those.

00:19:33.300 --> 00:19:36.140
My environment here is very dynamic I have
to say.

00:19:36.140 --> 00:19:37.140
[laughter]

00:19:37.140 --> 00:19:38.140
You're lighting up and down.

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:40.300
We're in the brain right here.

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:43.780
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #1: It's task oriented,
watching the brain.

00:19:43.780 --> 00:19:44.780
&gt;&gt;Dario Nardi: Yes.

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:45.780
Yes.

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:46.780
Yeah.

00:19:46.780 --> 00:19:47.780
We're inside the Google brain.

00:19:47.780 --> 00:19:52.080
So, this is what I was coming with, is I would
see--.

00:19:52.080 --> 00:19:55.370
What I would do over the two or three hours
is I would average the brain activity.

00:19:55.370 --> 00:19:59.420
That's not the only thing I do, but statistically,
it makes it really easy when you have 50 or

00:19:59.420 --> 00:20:01.320
60 megabytes of data.

00:20:01.320 --> 00:20:03.300
And these are real people.

00:20:03.300 --> 00:20:04.750
They're not their real names.

00:20:04.750 --> 00:20:07.270
But I have Maria and Ross here.

00:20:07.270 --> 00:20:10.830
And they happen to identify with the these
particular personality types.

00:20:10.830 --> 00:20:13.740
And I had ten weeks to let them get to this
best fit process.

00:20:13.740 --> 00:20:16.440
So, I felt that was very important in doing
research.

00:20:16.440 --> 00:20:20.890
If you're gonna make connections to personality,
you better make sure that it's an accurate

00:20:20.890 --> 00:20:22.880
connection.

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:26.690
And again, red regions are the most active.

00:20:26.690 --> 00:20:30.490
And then yellow and going all the way down--green,
blue, and then black.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:33.030
And they look quite different from each other,
don't they?

00:20:33.030 --> 00:20:34.990
Really, really quite different.

00:20:34.990 --> 00:20:39.310
But one thing we notice is that the--I'll
point to this one.

00:20:39.310 --> 00:20:42.430
I'm afraid of walking too far over there.

00:20:42.430 --> 00:20:49.620
This region here, this one here, there's really
on average no brain activity, which is remarkable.

00:20:49.620 --> 00:20:51.810
But there's this nice halo.

00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:54.950
And this is very light because it's just blue,
light activity.

00:20:54.950 --> 00:20:59.350
This little bridge across the halo here.

00:20:59.350 --> 00:21:04.520
Others might describe it as the rim of a volcano,
but because she happens to identify with INFP

00:21:04.520 --> 00:21:10.190
and I think INFPs prefer the halo metaphor,
as good and evil.

00:21:10.190 --> 00:21:11.190
[laughter]

00:21:11.190 --> 00:21:13.120
Over here, you can see the letters are very
different.

00:21:13.120 --> 00:21:18.440
So, even if you're not that up to date with
the Myers-Briggs terminology, it's absolutely

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:19.440
fine.

00:21:19.440 --> 00:21:24.450
You can tell that I versus E and N versus
S, F versus T. They're pretty different from

00:21:24.450 --> 00:21:25.450
each other.

00:21:25.450 --> 00:21:30.180
And in the interior here, they're practically
mirror images.

00:21:30.180 --> 00:21:36.120
At the same time I was doing these experiments,
I was also reading quite a bit about what

00:21:36.120 --> 00:21:42.410
others have discovered, primarily using EEG,
but other technologies like fMRI as well,

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:45.040
what these different regions tend to do.

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:48.520
And as I mentioned, the regions are a little
bit arbitrary.

00:21:48.520 --> 00:21:51.510
But we could be more fine-grained about it.

00:21:51.510 --> 00:21:55.500
So, sometimes there's some overlap in what
goes on.

00:21:55.500 --> 00:21:56.620
But I wanted to know.

00:21:56.620 --> 00:21:58.490
So, what does this mean?

00:21:58.490 --> 00:22:01.070
They're showing these consistent use of these
regions.

00:22:01.070 --> 00:22:03.090
Does this say anything about their personality?

00:22:03.090 --> 00:22:08.450
I did discover, and we'll just point out the
red regions here, that on this side here,

00:22:08.450 --> 00:22:11.830
this is for listening to words, specifically.

00:22:11.830 --> 00:22:14.980
So, diction, grammar, word selection.

00:22:14.980 --> 00:22:19.540
Not like a logical word selection, necessarily,
but at least what fits grammatically.

00:22:19.540 --> 00:22:23.350
Over here on this side, at least for right-handed
folks, this is about tone of voice.

00:22:23.350 --> 00:22:25.900
So, listening to tone of voice.

00:22:25.900 --> 00:22:31.390
So, part of tone of voice, there's a little
region around here that branches over to this

00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:38.760
area slightly, which is responsible for evaluating
intention, motivation.

00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:43.270
So if you ever wonder how come I better assess
people's intentions, will hopefully stimulate

00:22:43.270 --> 00:22:45.510
the neighboring area.

00:22:45.510 --> 00:22:48.320
Get that, pay attention to tone of voice and
what's going on there.

00:22:48.320 --> 00:22:52.270
So, when people emphasize words, that'll tell
you right there.

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:55.230
You also notice this region up here is red.

00:22:55.230 --> 00:22:57.140
This does two different things.

00:22:57.140 --> 00:23:01.650
And this actually was really well flushed
out by the work with autism because autistic

00:23:01.650 --> 00:23:06.770
individuals tend to have a lot more activity
here than on this side.

00:23:06.770 --> 00:23:10.800
And this region, one that handles how much
you like or dislike something.

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:15.960
So, when a musician would come in and he would
say "my guitar" and "my music."

00:23:15.960 --> 00:23:20.510
Every time he would say "my guitar" and "my
music," this region would light up--whatever

00:23:20.510 --> 00:23:21.650
happens to be important to you.

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:24.150
Now, some people will say a meta-type of statement.

00:23:24.150 --> 00:23:27.050
So, they'd be like "my values."

00:23:27.050 --> 00:23:29.260
And that will light it up as well.

00:23:29.260 --> 00:23:32.700
The region also handles something else.

00:23:32.700 --> 00:23:39.070
It really gets active when people remember
detailed information accurately.

00:23:39.070 --> 00:23:41.270
And at first, this was thought to be a little
bit strange.

00:23:41.270 --> 00:23:45.740
Like, why is it that something for like and
dislike, belief, and in fact, this region

00:23:45.740 --> 00:23:47.840
is also associated with religious beliefs.

00:23:47.840 --> 00:23:53.180
When people talk about their religious beliefs,
your religious beliefs, this region gets active,

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:54.190
too.

00:23:54.190 --> 00:23:56.960
Why would it also be related to detail?

00:23:56.960 --> 00:24:00.700
But if you tease it apart, you understand
really quickly what's going on.

00:24:00.700 --> 00:24:05.730
If something is important to you, it's not
just happens to be important say, here today

00:24:05.730 --> 00:24:07.040
at Google.

00:24:07.040 --> 00:24:10.350
It's something that is important generally
speaking across your life, no matter what

00:24:10.350 --> 00:24:12.340
situation it is.

00:24:12.340 --> 00:24:17.950
And so, you take those beliefs with you as
something that holds across different contexts.

00:24:17.950 --> 00:24:24.330
The reason this region gets active around
detail is a lot of the time, people get information.

00:24:24.330 --> 00:24:28.130
And then we ask, "What did you do earlier
this morning?"

00:24:28.130 --> 00:24:29.550
You may not remember every detail.

00:24:29.550 --> 00:24:32.380
You don't need to because you can fill in
with context.

00:24:32.380 --> 00:24:35.580
It's like, were there other cars on the road
this morning?

00:24:35.580 --> 00:24:40.460
You probably weren't paying attention to specifically,
was somebody gonna ask me later how many cars

00:24:40.460 --> 00:24:45.830
did I see, but you can guess pretty well based
on context and past experience.

00:24:45.830 --> 00:24:49.960
But guessing based on context is handled on
the other side.

00:24:49.960 --> 00:24:54.860
When this side is more active, it's again
about, "we're not gonna pay attention to context"--this

00:24:54.860 --> 00:24:57.060
idea that something that holds across situations.

00:24:57.060 --> 00:25:00.940
So, if we forget about context, we're not
gonna do any guessing in context.

00:25:00.940 --> 00:25:03.440
We're always gonna think something is true
no matter what.

00:25:03.440 --> 00:25:08.620
Now we understand why this region is really
good with detail because the detail--we're

00:25:08.620 --> 00:25:10.800
not trying to fill in the blanks or do guessing.

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:13.670
It's just what we remember and that's it.

00:25:13.670 --> 00:25:16.180
Finally, this region over here.

00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:18.700
So this is right up here on the front.

00:25:18.700 --> 00:25:21.700
This is really, really important, this region,
on both sides.

00:25:21.700 --> 00:25:25.660
These are the executives.

00:25:25.660 --> 00:25:27.640
Sometimes we can think of them as CEOs.

00:25:27.640 --> 00:25:32.400
Now, what is a company like when it has two
CEOs of equal power and authority?

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:36.200
Well, that's a really interesting question,
actually, to ask at this company.

00:25:36.200 --> 00:25:37.200
[laughter]

00:25:37.200 --> 00:25:38.940
But it's a little bit different.

00:25:38.940 --> 00:25:40.790
People still have defined roles.

00:25:40.790 --> 00:25:44.580
And there's a difference between founders
and then all the responsibilities that happen

00:25:44.580 --> 00:25:45.790
for day to day.

00:25:45.790 --> 00:25:46.790
And it can work out.

00:25:46.790 --> 00:25:51.970
But for the most part, people have a preference
for one side or the other--either this executive

00:25:51.970 --> 00:25:54.230
or this executive, even if they're right-handed.

00:25:54.230 --> 00:25:58.870
So, the stereotype is all right-handed folks
are more active on this left side over here,

00:25:58.870 --> 00:26:01.020
but that's actually not the case.

00:26:01.020 --> 00:26:06.950
It has more to do with personality type than
it does handedness.

00:26:06.950 --> 00:26:09.990
This region here is for explaining and deciding.

00:26:09.990 --> 00:26:14.570
So, if I give you three fingers, which finger
do you like the most?

00:26:14.570 --> 00:26:17.380
&gt;&gt;FEMALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #2: Not the middle
one.

00:26:17.380 --> 00:26:18.380
&gt;&gt;Dario Nardi: OK.

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:19.380
So it's gonna be this one here.

00:26:19.380 --> 00:26:20.380
OK, good choice.

00:26:20.380 --> 00:26:21.380
OK.

00:26:21.380 --> 00:26:22.380
And then, why did you select that one?

00:26:22.380 --> 00:26:23.380
&gt;&gt;FEMALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #2: It's very useful.

00:26:23.380 --> 00:26:24.380
&gt;&gt;Dario Nardi: Very useful.

00:26:24.380 --> 00:26:26.420
OK, where you can point with it and this and
that and it's not the middle one.

00:26:26.420 --> 00:26:28.170
So, you've made a choice.

00:26:28.170 --> 00:26:30.990
You've done some decision-making and you gave
an explanation.

00:26:30.990 --> 00:26:34.630
We might think, "Oh, was that a logical explanation
you gave?"

00:26:34.630 --> 00:26:38.310
But if you actually had to work out the logic
as you were speaking, like, the situation

00:26:38.310 --> 00:26:39.370
would go on.

00:26:39.370 --> 00:26:43.350
But it takes so long to work out the logic
of "is that really the logical choice?"

00:26:43.350 --> 00:26:45.620
So, most of the time, we don't actually use
our whole brain.

00:26:45.620 --> 00:26:49.520
It feels like we're thinking and making logical
decisions, but actually it's just the executive

00:26:49.520 --> 00:26:54.040
making up something that sounds perfectly
reasonable and it's pretty workable.

00:26:54.040 --> 00:26:56.350
And that's what goes on with this region right
here.

00:26:56.350 --> 00:27:02.150
So, I suppose you could say INFPs are really
good at coming up with reasons and explanations

00:27:02.150 --> 00:27:07.400
and making long-term life decisions that revolve
around their personal identity and values.

00:27:07.400 --> 00:27:11.480
And they're very good at listening and working
with words, whether those are literal words

00:27:11.480 --> 00:27:15.280
and composition, word choice, or perhaps reading.

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:16.280
It's not just writing.

00:27:16.280 --> 00:27:17.280
It's reading as well.

00:27:17.280 --> 00:27:21.720
And also attentive to tone of voice and intentionality.

00:27:21.720 --> 00:27:23.990
And so, if you're a little bit aware of Myers-Briggs,
great.

00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:30.060
That sounds like a good match with INFP, especially
when we notice that the yellow sections over

00:27:30.060 --> 00:27:34.070
here, that these are related to the areas
of asking "What if?"

00:27:34.070 --> 00:27:36.880
And visualizing some possibilities.

00:27:36.880 --> 00:27:40.400
And down here, this is also noticing visual
impressions.

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:45.630
If you don't know Myers-Briggs, I've actually
given you a pretty good description of INFP

00:27:45.630 --> 00:27:48.980
in terms of their capabilities, or their skill
set.

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:52.500
This was really wonderful to see that match
that was there.

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:54.530
Conversely, ESTP.

00:27:54.530 --> 00:27:59.310
I won't go into detail about this one, but
you can see that the other executive is the

00:27:59.310 --> 00:28:01.260
one that's more in charge.

00:28:01.260 --> 00:28:06.980
And this side over here, this side here, is
much more about managing process, for allowing

00:28:06.980 --> 00:28:14.380
more information in and dwelling on that information
and allowing it to affect what it is that

00:28:14.380 --> 00:28:16.090
you do.

00:28:16.090 --> 00:28:19.160
These regions here are for logical reasoning.

