00:30:55.380 --> 00:31:00.700
Would I be able to guess the person's Myers-Briggs
type?

00:31:00.700 --> 00:31:03.300
And I would say quite a bit of the time, yes.

00:31:03.300 --> 00:31:07.270
Right away there's the, is this side or this
side more active?

00:31:07.270 --> 00:31:10.340
That will immediately narrow down from 16
to eight.

00:31:10.340 --> 00:31:14.520
And from there, I might do something like,
are one or more of these regions on the interior

00:31:14.520 --> 00:31:19.490
active that indicates an interest in--it's
called introverted thinking.

00:31:19.490 --> 00:31:23.560
It's not the same as being an introvert with
the thinking preference, but we'll get to

00:31:23.560 --> 00:31:24.560
that.

00:31:24.560 --> 00:31:26.910
Do they have a lot of listening?

00:31:26.910 --> 00:31:30.830
The same folks who show a lot of activity
in the middle here, tend to have a lot less

00:31:30.830 --> 00:31:31.830
listening.

00:31:31.830 --> 00:31:34.800
So, that would be a sort right there as well.

00:31:34.800 --> 00:31:36.391
I've seen the halo a number of times.

00:31:36.391 --> 00:31:42.260
I've had seven INFP subjects and you can pretty
well tell them, not just from this activity

00:31:42.260 --> 00:31:46.470
here, but what I'm also gonna describe is
the whole brain activity that happens.

00:31:46.470 --> 00:31:50.370
And no, I would say though still, everyone
is unique.

00:31:50.370 --> 00:31:55.050
Like, that's why I start with Maria, who happens,
in parenthesis, to identify with INFP.

00:31:55.050 --> 00:32:00.130
'Cause I've had other INFPs, let’s say one
who does sports, and he had much more activity

00:32:00.130 --> 00:32:04.470
in this region here, which would be very useful
for doing sports.

00:32:04.470 --> 00:32:09.190
So, a person's background and their skill
sets will definitely do it.

00:32:09.190 --> 00:32:10.250
So, I'm just gonna--.

00:32:10.250 --> 00:32:14.460
I'm not gonna go through all of this, but
give you a sense of what it is that ends up

00:32:14.460 --> 00:32:15.920
on this chart.

00:32:15.920 --> 00:32:19.580
Everything that I put up here is both found
in the literature, so not by me.

00:32:19.580 --> 00:32:21.230
Other people have located these things.

00:32:21.230 --> 00:32:22.840
And I saw it.

00:32:22.840 --> 00:32:25.730
It worked out in my lab from the lab data.

00:32:25.730 --> 00:32:28.980
And I didn’t want to talk about anything
that wouldn't meet those two criteria.

00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:33.650
I thought it was really important to be able
to say, "Yes, this is happening here on someone

00:32:33.650 --> 00:32:35.220
and I've seen it for real."

00:32:35.220 --> 00:32:40.000
Otherwise, it's so easy to draw connection
between what I read and thinking like, "Oh,

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:41.000
yeah.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:42.000
That sounds like such and such."

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:47.580
The other thing you'll notice, you may have
stumbled across some theories about maybe

00:32:47.580 --> 00:32:53.131
people are more left-brained or right-brained
if they use more of one quadrant of the brain

00:32:53.131 --> 00:32:54.430
over the other.

00:32:54.430 --> 00:32:55.430
Sorry.

00:32:55.430 --> 00:33:01.600
Our brains are much more complex and interesting
than just having a simple left and right or

00:33:01.600 --> 00:33:03.450
different quadrants, something like that.

00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:09.370
Like, all these regions, and really, these
are the results of evolutionary forces.

00:33:09.370 --> 00:33:13.440
So sometimes you have things grouped together
in you're like, "Well, why aren't these neighbors?"

00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:14.440
I don't know.

00:33:14.440 --> 00:33:18.180
That's just the way it worked out.

00:33:18.180 --> 00:33:24.260
And down here, this section on doing mathematics
and integrating vision and sensation, that

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:26.690
also comes as reading.

00:33:26.690 --> 00:33:34.410
I had a woman from Saudi Arabia asking, "Why
is it that going to a Koranic school where

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:35.410
they memorize--.

00:33:35.410 --> 00:33:38.960
They read the Koran and they memorize it and
repeat it verbally.

00:33:38.960 --> 00:33:41.330
Why is it that it improves their ability in
mathematics?"

00:33:41.330 --> 00:33:45.300
I said this actually is really not a surprise
because reading and math and both, especially

00:33:45.300 --> 00:33:51.380
rote mathematics--so what is five times five,
kind of thing--and reading are both really

00:33:51.380 --> 00:33:55.550
heavily associated with this one region right
here.

00:33:55.550 --> 00:34:01.410
And so, there was a natural carry over between
those.

00:34:01.410 --> 00:34:08.679
This is a favorite for folks who use the personality
type to explain preference.

00:34:08.679 --> 00:34:10.929
And I thought, "Oh, this will be really great
example.

00:34:10.929 --> 00:34:13.620
I'll just try this in the lab and see what
happens."

00:34:13.620 --> 00:34:16.659
And I was actually ended being really shocked.

00:34:16.659 --> 00:34:22.730
This one exercise turns out to be a fantastic
sorter between S in the code or N in the code.

00:34:22.730 --> 00:34:26.770
So, I asked them to sign their name with their
preferred hand.

00:34:26.770 --> 00:34:28.419
And then I asked them to sign again.

00:34:28.419 --> 00:34:30.270
Actually they do several things.

00:34:30.270 --> 00:34:34.460
They sign again with their non-preferred hand
and then they sign again backwards, but with

00:34:34.460 --> 00:34:35.480
their preferred hand.

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:41.020
And then sign yet again, a fourth time, backwards
with their non-preferred hand.

00:34:41.020 --> 00:34:47.610
And the expectation, we might think is a common
sense hypothesis, that signing your name should

00:34:47.610 --> 00:34:50.450
not require too much work.

00:34:50.450 --> 00:34:53.080
And it won't evoke too much brain activity.

00:34:53.080 --> 00:34:58.300
But signing your name again with your non-preferred
hand backwards will definitely, it should

00:34:58.300 --> 00:34:59.670
evoke more activity, right?

00:34:59.670 --> 00:35:04.440
You're trying to figure out which letter comes
next and you have to work your hand, knowing

00:35:04.440 --> 00:35:06.760
how to be left-handed about it and how does
it go.

00:35:06.760 --> 00:35:08.660
So, I thought well, this is gonna be easy.

00:35:08.660 --> 00:35:12.880
I'm just gonna demonstrate signing with your
non-preferred hand takes more work in the

00:35:12.880 --> 00:35:13.880
brain.

00:35:13.880 --> 00:35:15.180
And I was wrong.

00:35:15.180 --> 00:35:16.410
I wasn't completely wrong.

00:35:16.410 --> 00:35:20.730
It turns out that folks who have an intuiting
preference, so they have an N in their type

00:35:20.730 --> 00:35:23.180
code, that that holds true.

00:35:23.180 --> 00:35:26.960
They try harder with the second activity.

00:35:26.960 --> 00:35:32.720
For folks who have sensing preference, they
have an S in their code, it's actually the

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:33.720
reverse.

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:35.630
That signing their name, you see some brain
activity.

00:35:35.630 --> 00:35:39.580
And when I asked them to do, sign backwards
with your non-preferred hand, it doesn't really

00:35:39.580 --> 00:35:41.480
show any activity.

00:35:41.480 --> 00:35:43.880
Now why might that be?

00:35:43.880 --> 00:35:51.100
Well, as one student said--he had a sensing
preference--"Signing your name backwards with

00:35:51.100 --> 00:35:56.200
your non-preferred hand, that's just some
random, weird fun activity to do.

00:35:56.200 --> 00:35:58.000
Like, that doesn't have any meaning to it.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:35:59.830
Like when would I do that in real life?"

00:35:59.830 --> 00:36:01.380
So, there was no attempt.

00:36:01.380 --> 00:36:04.740
It's not important, which really highlighted
to me that motivation.

00:36:04.740 --> 00:36:06.120
It's not just about competence.

00:36:06.120 --> 00:36:08.270
It's about motivation as well.

00:36:08.270 --> 00:36:13.730
Whereas for some of the sensing preference,
often signing your name really nicely is important

00:36:13.730 --> 00:36:14.730
to them.

00:36:14.730 --> 00:36:17.230
They don't just randomly repeat it.

00:36:17.230 --> 00:36:20.200
There's actually some brain activity that
goes into it.

00:36:20.200 --> 00:36:23.840
And that got me thinking that maybe there's
something interesting going on.

00:36:23.840 --> 00:36:26.190
And then I really tried that out more.

00:36:26.190 --> 00:36:29.850
And I had a student who knew French and Arabic
and English.

00:36:29.850 --> 00:36:30.970
And I said, "Fantastic."

00:36:30.970 --> 00:36:32.840
And he's very good at English.

00:36:32.840 --> 00:36:36.600
You wouldn't know that Arabic was his original
native language.

00:36:36.600 --> 00:36:41.600
And I said, "Could you write your name in
Arabic backwards with your non-preferred hand

00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:44.260
in addition to writing it the usual way."

00:36:44.260 --> 00:36:45.870
And he had an intuiting preference.

00:36:45.870 --> 00:36:49.780
So, I thought, "Writing his name in Arabic,
it's gonna be no brain activity.

00:36:49.780 --> 00:36:52.670
And writing his name backwards in Arabic,
it'll evoke more brain activity."

00:36:52.670 --> 00:36:53.670
Didn't happen.

00:36:53.670 --> 00:36:54.820
Why not?

00:36:54.820 --> 00:36:58.530
I said, "You didn't show any brain activity
here."

00:36:58.530 --> 00:37:01.510
After we debriefed the task.

00:37:01.510 --> 00:37:03.200
What happened?

00:37:03.200 --> 00:37:06.400
And he said, "Well, none of you in the lab
can read Arabic, so it didn't matter how I

00:37:06.400 --> 00:37:07.400
wrote."

00:37:07.400 --> 00:37:08.400
[laughter]

00:37:08.400 --> 00:37:10.010
So, it really was--.

00:37:10.010 --> 00:37:11.920
I'm like, "Oh.

00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:12.920
Of course."

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:18.010
So really, the motivation and context do play
an essential part in how it is that we use

00:37:18.010 --> 00:37:19.010
our brains.

00:37:19.010 --> 00:37:21.520
So, competence plus motivation together.

00:37:21.520 --> 00:37:25.940
And that's then what I call this engagement
curve.

00:37:25.940 --> 00:37:30.460
Being engaged means being competent and/or
motivated, preferably and.

00:37:30.460 --> 00:37:33.920
I think we can be somewhat engaged if we have
competence just because--.

00:37:33.920 --> 00:37:40.010
I don't really, I'm not like a big math nerd
or something, but I did a lot of math.

00:37:40.010 --> 00:37:44.890
I did probably three solid years of calculus--linear
algebra and the matrices and all that kind

00:37:44.890 --> 00:37:47.920
of stuff as an engineering student.

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:50.600
I don't remember any of it.

00:37:50.600 --> 00:37:55.670
I recognize what part of the book I need to
look to understand to do it, but that's it.

00:37:55.670 --> 00:37:57.010
So yeah, I could do that.

00:37:57.010 --> 00:38:00.860
Also, somebody could be motivated and terrible
at it, but they're gonna try.

00:38:00.860 --> 00:38:02.310
But ideally, it's both.

00:38:02.310 --> 00:38:08.400
So engaging activities evoke progressively
more brain activity as challenge and motivation

00:38:08.400 --> 00:38:09.400
increase.

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:12.570
So, assuming the student is motivated to do
the math problems and not look like a fool

00:38:12.570 --> 00:38:17.380
because they can't subtract 17 from 34.

00:38:17.380 --> 00:38:23.710
As the problems get more challenging, this
curve will move up, assuming they're motivated.

00:38:23.710 --> 00:38:26.910
The moment they reach the point where they're
like, "Oh, I don't know this math.

00:38:26.910 --> 00:38:27.910
I can't do it."

00:38:27.910 --> 00:38:29.550
And they give up on it.

00:38:29.550 --> 00:38:31.280
The motivation is lost.

00:38:31.280 --> 00:38:33.300
There's an instant drop in brain activity.

00:38:33.300 --> 00:38:36.700
So, it really could go in a particular, several
regions.

00:38:36.700 --> 00:38:38.080
One, two, three.

00:38:38.080 --> 00:38:41.520
Goes from blue to green to yellow to finally
some red that's there.

00:38:41.520 --> 00:38:43.010
And it just drops off to black.

00:38:43.010 --> 00:38:44.010
Nothing.

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:48.480
So, if I said, "Please all of you now take
a moment to sign your name in Urdu."

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:50.940
There might be one person who can, OK?

00:38:50.940 --> 00:38:53.220
But for most of you, probably not.

00:38:53.220 --> 00:38:56.870
So I think that's really important and that's
one of the things that I hear about 'cause

00:38:56.870 --> 00:39:01.680
I don't see it firsthand, but I hear Google
really is very welcoming for their employees

00:39:01.680 --> 00:39:06.340
to have time to do their own projects, which
is great because presumably you're motivated

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:07.380
to do your own projects.

00:39:07.380 --> 00:39:10.020
And you're picking something that you have
some competence in.

00:39:10.020 --> 00:39:16.720
So, that is going to engage you and get you
in there.

00:39:16.720 --> 00:39:19.130
Now I'm talking about some of these holistic
activities.

00:39:19.130 --> 00:39:21.180
This is--.

00:39:21.180 --> 00:39:25.170
It comes out a light blue.

00:39:25.170 --> 00:39:27.010
It's darker blue here.

00:39:27.010 --> 00:39:33.190
It should be like the color of the sky because
the brightness reflects something as well

00:39:33.190 --> 00:39:35.680
as just the frequency of the color.

00:39:35.680 --> 00:39:39.840
This is every region is in sync with every
other region.

00:39:39.840 --> 00:39:45.820
All of them have the same, or dominated by
the same frequency and amplitude of electromagnetic

00:39:45.820 --> 00:39:46.820
activity.

00:39:46.820 --> 00:39:47.820
What does that mean?

00:39:47.820 --> 00:39:51.870
That means it's not just a mansion filled
with rooms and each person is doing their

00:39:51.870 --> 00:39:52.870
own thing.

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:57.780
It's everybody's in sync and working with
everyone else.

00:39:57.780 --> 00:39:59.820
People can maintain this for a few seconds.

00:39:59.820 --> 00:40:05.420
So, you win at a hand of cards, or even just
the process of shuffling cards may evoke this.

00:40:05.420 --> 00:40:10.400
Or, it may remain there for two minutes, three
minutes, ten minutes, whatever it is.

00:40:10.400 --> 00:40:12.820
And when doing a task as an expert--.

00:40:12.820 --> 00:40:17.620
There's actually an exception to this and
that relates to two of the personality types.

00:40:17.620 --> 00:40:20.050
But let's take a look at what are those activities.

00:40:20.050 --> 00:40:24.450
What the question that you might consider
as we look through these, are any of these

00:40:24.450 --> 00:40:26.250
like what you do?

00:40:26.250 --> 00:40:29.630
And it was interesting because somebody asked
me, "Do people know when they're in the state

00:40:29.630 --> 00:40:30.630
of flow?"

00:40:30.630 --> 00:40:34.580
Sort of, do we have some kind of self-reflective
intuition?

00:40:34.580 --> 00:40:35.580
Something like that.

00:40:35.580 --> 00:40:37.340
I don't think so from my lab.

00:40:37.340 --> 00:40:43.350
Like, none of them could report when they
thought they showed this or not.

00:40:43.350 --> 00:40:44.670
So then, I think it's important to then--.

00:40:44.670 --> 00:40:48.700
Actually, this is an example why knowing personality
type would be really helpful because in general,

00:40:48.700 --> 00:40:52.960
these were associated with either your skill
area, like music or dance, something like

00:40:52.960 --> 00:40:56.650
that, or they were related to the person's
personality type.

00:40:56.650 --> 00:40:57.650
Acting.

00:40:57.650 --> 00:41:00.770
By following a highly rehearsed scene--.

00:41:00.770 --> 00:41:08.132
So, we had an actor, an EFNP actor by the
way, and when he did a cold reading it didn't

00:41:08.132 --> 00:41:09.240
show up.

00:41:09.240 --> 00:41:12.740
And when he did improvisational acting, it
didn't show up either.

00:41:12.740 --> 00:41:13.990
It was only doing--.

00:41:13.990 --> 00:41:18.330
What ENFPs love to do, right, which is lots
of memorization and rehearsal?

00:41:18.330 --> 00:41:19.330
No.

00:41:19.330 --> 00:41:23.380
But that's when they reach the state of flow
is after he really forced himself to spend

00:41:23.380 --> 00:41:27.220
all this time repetitions, doing practice.

00:41:27.220 --> 00:41:29.210
Describing the ultimate meaning of why people
live or die.

00:41:29.210 --> 00:41:35.080
So, I give out this little news article and
usually I read it to the person.

00:41:35.080 --> 00:41:39.580
And it's a fictitious article and it's about
something sad that reflects a little bit of

00:41:39.580 --> 00:41:43.840
your responsibility from one of the people
mentioned in the article.

00:41:43.840 --> 00:41:45.311
And after I read it--.

00:41:45.311 --> 00:41:47.090
And it involves death.

00:41:47.090 --> 00:41:51.570
And after I read it, I ask people to use one
or two words to describe how you feel right

00:41:51.570 --> 00:41:52.570
now.

00:41:52.570 --> 00:41:56.990
And most people will say, "I'm sad," or "I'm
angry," or some combination thereof.

00:41:56.990 --> 00:42:05.120
However, this one student with ENFJ preferences,
E-N-F-J, refused to answer with one or two

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:06.120
emotions.

00:42:06.120 --> 00:42:07.120
She said, "That's too easy.

00:42:07.120 --> 00:42:08.120
That's childish."

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:10.730
It would be so easy to just say I'm angry
or I'm sad.

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:15.450
So she began to give a philosophical reason
for why people are put on the earth and what

00:42:15.450 --> 00:42:18.150
are our responsibilities to each other as
human beings.

00:42:18.150 --> 00:42:22.250
And all the while, while she's giving me this
and answer and drawing from the article and

00:42:22.250 --> 00:42:26.730
composing a response that fits with her philosophy,
there was solid blue.

00:42:26.730 --> 00:42:31.820
Every region was participating, contributing,
to her philosophical response.

00:42:31.820 --> 00:42:37.470
In contrast, by the way, her opposite type,
ISTP, I had a student like that recently.

00:42:37.470 --> 00:42:40.060
I read the same article and asked the same
questions.

00:42:40.060 --> 00:42:41.930
And the ISTP, she said to me--.

00:42:41.930 --> 00:42:43.581
I asked, "How do you feel in one or two words."

00:42:43.581 --> 00:42:45.930
And she said, "I feel nothing."

00:42:45.930 --> 00:42:48.580
She says, "I wasn't there.

00:42:48.580 --> 00:42:50.530
It didn't involve anyone I know.

00:42:50.530 --> 00:42:55.869
I haven't really had time to think about how
I feel."

00:42:55.869 --> 00:43:00.270
So I think that was even, even not just looking
at brain activity, but just listening and

00:43:00.270 --> 00:43:05.000
watching how people do activities in the lab
and the kind of responses they give are--.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:10.320
It never occurred to me that someone would
have no emotional response to it.

00:43:10.320 --> 00:43:14.190
She said "if you give me some time to think
about it and I read it over again, I can give

00:43:14.190 --> 00:43:16.170
you an emotional response."

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:20.890
That's sort of, you have to manufacture where
you send it to the plant and they make it

00:43:20.890 --> 00:43:23.610
and bring it back.

00:43:23.610 --> 00:43:25.620
[laughter]

00:43:25.620 --> 00:43:34.330
My younger brother has ISTP preferences and
he used to do a lot of track racing and I

00:43:34.330 --> 00:43:36.580
asked him after a win how he felt.

00:43:36.580 --> 00:43:38.410
And he said, "I think I feel happy."

00:43:38.410 --> 00:43:42.370
I'm like, "But how do you feel?"

00:43:42.370 --> 00:43:43.370
[laughter]

00:43:43.370 --> 00:43:44.370
Drumming a familiar beat.

00:43:44.370 --> 00:43:49.040
So, we had a drummer and when she drummed
her favorite familiar beat, not other times,

00:43:49.040 --> 00:43:50.170
but when she did that.

00:43:50.170 --> 00:43:52.360
Handling a dramatic crisis in a role play
scenario.

00:43:52.360 --> 00:43:57.830
So, this is what I've seen with all the types
with S and P in their code, especially ESFP

00:43:57.830 --> 00:43:59.180
and ESTP.

00:43:59.180 --> 00:44:02.680
As the actors come in, the theater students,
they can get up.

00:44:02.680 --> 00:44:03.740
So the subject can get up.

00:44:03.740 --> 00:44:05.360
They can't swivel their head around a lot.

00:44:05.360 --> 00:44:08.670
I discourage that, but otherwise they can
move a little bit.

00:44:08.670 --> 00:44:12.119
And they're engaged in a crisis role play
and they like getting into it.

00:44:12.119 --> 00:44:14.550
They absolutely do.

00:44:14.550 --> 00:44:15.550
And they're very creative.

00:44:15.550 --> 00:44:18.670
They pick topics that I would never think
of, involving--.

00:44:18.670 --> 00:44:22.660
Well, I won't even get into it.

00:44:22.660 --> 00:44:24.270
Things that are not repeatable here.

00:44:24.270 --> 00:44:27.910
But they know Dario was cool and will be OK
with it.

00:44:27.910 --> 00:44:30.981
[audience chuckles] So, as they get into it,
they go from having brain activity about listening

00:44:30.981 --> 00:44:36.640
and seeing and so on, and all of a sudden,
as it ramps up the crisis, their brain show

00:44:36.640 --> 00:44:40.660
a little blue here and blue there and some
regions starting to hold and then disappear.

00:44:40.660 --> 00:44:43.770
And then they just hold like this, really
tightly.

00:44:43.770 --> 00:44:47.680
And they remain there for two or three minutes
until the crisis began to resolve itself and

00:44:47.680 --> 00:44:50.290
then it would slowly start to come apart again.

00:44:50.290 --> 00:44:55.340
So, the ability to be in a state of flow with
a crisis--and they didn't know what was gonna

00:44:55.340 --> 00:44:56.369
happen next.

00:44:56.369 --> 00:45:00.390
So I wouldn't say that that was an area of
expertise, except maybe they're good at crisis

00:45:00.390 --> 00:45:04.560
management and good at role play in the situations.

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:06.640
Listening intently to somebody else.

00:45:06.640 --> 00:45:11.650
I've had some students who can debate contentious
topics, like gun control.

00:45:11.650 --> 00:45:15.310
And by some, I mean only the INFPs.

00:45:15.310 --> 00:45:17.330
And maybe some ISFPs a little bit as well.

00:45:17.330 --> 00:45:20.730
So, those are two types that have a lot of
similarities to each other.

00:45:20.730 --> 00:45:22.650
They're good listeners.

00:45:22.650 --> 00:45:24.470
One student, he sat--.

00:45:24.470 --> 00:45:29.290
And you know normally, when we hear something
we disagree with, what is our natural response?

00:45:29.290 --> 00:45:34.680
It's to come up with counter arguments, even
as the other person is still speaking.

00:45:34.680 --> 00:45:38.180
'Cause we sorta guess what they're gonna say
and we come up with again with what is our

00:45:38.180 --> 00:45:39.180
own view.

00:45:39.180 --> 00:45:40.230
He didn't do that.

00:45:40.230 --> 00:45:46.960
For ten solid minutes, whether he was speaking
or whether his argument, opponent, his opponent

00:45:46.960 --> 00:45:52.290
in the argument was speaking, he remained,
every region was in the state of awake, but

00:45:52.290 --> 00:45:54.010
alert.

00:45:54.010 --> 00:45:57.380
And then finally, after ten minutes that pattern
broke.

00:45:57.380 --> 00:46:03.260
And there was a lot of activity in the left
prefrontal areas as he decided and explained

00:46:03.260 --> 00:46:04.410
his final opinion.

00:46:04.410 --> 00:46:09.170
And he's like, "I gave you ten minutes to
give me your point of view and I really did

00:46:09.170 --> 00:46:10.170
consider it."

00:46:10.170 --> 00:46:12.010
So, that's what I mean by truly active listening.

00:46:12.010 --> 00:46:16.810
"And now, I have decided my perspective on
it."

00:46:16.810 --> 00:46:18.150
And that was the end of listening.

00:46:18.150 --> 00:46:21.630
So, I would say with folks who are really
good listeners, keep in mind they're not always

00:46:21.630 --> 00:46:22.730
really good listeners.

00:46:22.730 --> 00:46:25.530
Once they make up their mind that’s it.

00:46:25.530 --> 00:46:26.830
And it's great to see.

00:46:26.830 --> 00:46:29.140
Now I also had one student.

00:46:29.140 --> 00:46:34.410
He would only show the pattern of active listening
when he listened to me and another professor.

00:46:34.410 --> 00:46:37.440
So, this was about the central authority figures.

00:46:37.440 --> 00:46:38.880
Anyone know someone like that?

00:46:38.880 --> 00:46:42.390
Yeah, what did the authority say?

00:46:42.390 --> 00:46:48.300
I also had one student who would only listen
that way to women, but not to men.

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:53.840
And it was really funny 'cause he and his
fraternity brother were both in the lab.

00:46:53.840 --> 00:46:56.900
So, his fraternity brother could back this
up.

00:46:56.900 --> 00:46:59.210
The fraternity brothers made fun of him.

00:46:59.210 --> 00:47:01.190
They were always, "Kareem, you never listen.

00:47:01.190 --> 00:47:02.590
I mean, you never listen.

00:47:02.590 --> 00:47:03.590
You never do any chores.

00:47:03.590 --> 00:47:05.690
You don't remember to do anything when say
stuff to you.

00:47:05.690 --> 00:47:08.710
It just goes in one ear and out the other."

00:47:08.710 --> 00:47:11.560
And he said that just didn't make sense.

00:47:11.560 --> 00:47:16.650
And he was saying, "I have all these female
friends."

00:47:16.650 --> 00:47:22.270
He has, like to him, just keeping to one date
is difficult because they all want to date

00:47:22.270 --> 00:47:23.270
him.

00:47:23.270 --> 00:47:25.930
And all of them, he says, "My female friends
me, they're like, 'Kareem, you're a fantastic

00:47:25.930 --> 00:47:28.150
listener.'"

00:47:28.150 --> 00:47:29.790
And now we know why.

00:47:29.790 --> 00:47:34.690
He enters a state of active flow when he's
listening to women, but not to men.

00:47:34.690 --> 00:47:36.500
Maybe he might wanna work on that.

00:47:36.500 --> 00:47:38.060
I don't know.

00:47:38.060 --> 00:47:39.590
Pointing while talking, or using a finger.

00:47:39.590 --> 00:47:41.730
I always noticed my mom when she would read.

00:47:41.730 --> 00:47:42.730
She uses--.

00:47:42.730 --> 00:47:45.550
She never took a speed reading class, but
she uses her finger to read.

00:47:45.550 --> 00:47:46.990
And one time I asked her, "Why do you do that?"

00:47:46.990 --> 00:47:48.160
And she said, "It helps me focus."

00:47:48.160 --> 00:47:49.160
I'm like, "OK."

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:52.570
I don't feel like I need to use my finger
and I can focus.

00:47:52.570 --> 00:47:54.540
But I'll trust that it works for you.

00:47:54.540 --> 00:47:59.260
So, I saw a student do this in the lab of
a similar type and I said, "Hey, what's going

00:47:59.260 --> 00:48:00.260
on?"

00:48:00.260 --> 00:48:02.060
And he said, "Oh, it helps me focus."

00:48:02.060 --> 00:48:03.200
And so, the whole--.

00:48:03.200 --> 00:48:04.230
His finger was there.

00:48:04.230 --> 00:48:05.230
It was all blue.

00:48:05.230 --> 00:48:06.420
He takes the finger away.

00:48:06.420 --> 00:48:09.190
All of a sudden it breaks up into pretty much
nothing.

00:48:09.190 --> 00:48:10.190
I say, "OK.

00:48:10.190 --> 00:48:11.190
Now reapply your finger."

00:48:11.190 --> 00:48:12.190
It's suddenly blue again.

00:48:12.190 --> 00:48:13.250
"Take your finger away."

00:48:13.250 --> 00:48:15.130
I mean, really is like that fast.

00:48:15.130 --> 00:48:16.359
That's the great thing about EEG.

00:48:16.359 --> 00:48:17.859
It's like, instant.

00:48:17.859 --> 00:48:19.720
And I'm like, "Wow.

00:48:19.720 --> 00:48:21.190
Make sure you don't lose those fingers.

00:48:21.190 --> 00:48:24.020
And don't give them away to somebody else."

00:48:24.020 --> 00:48:25.020
[laughter]

00:48:25.020 --> 00:48:26.020
You want that.

00:48:26.020 --> 00:48:27.020
That's a good thing to know.

00:48:27.020 --> 00:48:29.340
So then there are all these other things that
came up.

00:48:29.340 --> 00:48:31.869
Reviewing the past or visualizing the future.

00:48:31.869 --> 00:48:35.450
If I asked you what your life is like or going
to be ten years from now.

00:48:35.450 --> 00:48:42.010
The natural tendency is to think about what
we'd like to happen or what stereotypically

00:48:42.010 --> 00:48:46.160
happens to people, or logically what will
probably happen.

00:48:46.160 --> 00:48:49.380
But some people really open up.

00:48:49.380 --> 00:48:52.610
Every region of the brain gets involved in
this state of flow.

00:48:52.610 --> 00:49:00.410
So, it's a coordinated, synchronized contribution
to say, "Yes, what will happen in the future."

00:49:00.410 --> 00:49:02.320
Or, for the past.

00:49:02.320 --> 00:49:03.320
The same thing.

00:49:03.320 --> 00:49:06.890
Review your life, something that happened
to you say, 20 years ago or--.

00:49:06.890 --> 00:49:09.350
Well, the students didn't necessarily live
that long.

00:49:09.350 --> 00:49:10.550
They won't remember.

00:49:10.550 --> 00:49:12.990
But, when they were kids.

00:49:12.990 --> 00:49:17.800
See, this is, I think, where some of the stuff
really began that might be relevant for you.

00:49:17.800 --> 00:49:18.890
Singing a unique song.

00:49:18.890 --> 00:49:21.330
So, the student was a musician playing guitar.

00:49:21.330 --> 00:49:25.140
He's a professional singer and guitar player.

00:49:25.140 --> 00:49:30.470
Singing other songs did not evoke that flow,
only when he did his own.

00:49:30.470 --> 00:49:34.150
Singing other songs, there would be like this
motor activity that goes on with the hands

00:49:34.150 --> 00:49:37.500
and so on--kinesthetic activity and some auditory.

00:49:37.500 --> 00:49:38.740
But it was doing his own stuff.

00:49:38.740 --> 00:49:41.090
For the entire song, he'd remain in that state.

00:49:41.090 --> 00:49:46.820
And I've seen this time and again that when
the students would do things that were directly

00:49:46.820 --> 00:49:48.030
related, was a unique product.

00:49:48.030 --> 00:49:50.310
So that's why I say it's more than expertise.

00:49:50.310 --> 00:49:54.760
A lot of times it's creative expertise, as
what the person has done individually, that

00:49:54.760 --> 00:49:56.070
really evokes that state.

00:49:56.070 --> 00:49:58.270
They internalized it and made their own.

00:49:58.270 --> 00:50:02.350
In fact, one student, she was a dancer for
15 years--from age three to age 18.

00:50:02.350 --> 00:50:05.160
So, that's probably pretty burnt into the
brain.

00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:10.440
All she had to do was sit back and relax,
close her eyes and visualize dancing.

00:50:10.440 --> 00:50:14.190
And every region of her brain was in sync
with every other.

00:50:14.190 --> 00:50:17.430
Now, sometimes this has interesting implications.

00:50:17.430 --> 00:50:22.940
I had a student sorting between his parents
wanted him to go to dental school and he wants

00:50:22.940 --> 00:50:26.300
to be a rap musician.

00:50:26.300 --> 00:50:27.300
Very different.

00:50:27.300 --> 00:50:30.160
And I guess the parent's feel like we've paid
for you to go to UCLA.

00:50:30.160 --> 00:50:33.470
Like, you're gonna graduate and become a dentist.

00:50:33.470 --> 00:50:34.650
And he comes from a Persian family.

00:50:34.650 --> 00:50:38.619
And if you may know, Persian families tend
to be very--how can we say--hands on with

00:50:38.619 --> 00:50:41.720
their kids in guiding them.

00:50:41.720 --> 00:50:44.680
And when we talked about dentistry, that didn't
really evoke any--.

00:50:44.680 --> 00:50:46.240
Even in this region up here about importance.

00:50:46.240 --> 00:50:48.530
It just did not evoke anything.

00:50:48.530 --> 00:50:52.390
When he did his own rap songs that he had
made up.

00:50:52.390 --> 00:50:56.640
So this is really funny 'cause this is like
a Persian guy, 20 years old, and he's singing

00:50:56.640 --> 00:50:58.990
like, ghetto rap songs.

00:50:58.990 --> 00:51:00.150
And even his own versions.

00:51:00.150 --> 00:51:03.760
And he went into this total state of blue
creative flow.

00:51:03.760 --> 00:51:08.400
So I just reported that to him that "you do
seem to have some kind of special affinity,

00:51:08.400 --> 00:51:11.560
talent, expertise, creative expertise with
this."

00:51:11.560 --> 00:51:16.100
I understand it's been like, four years since
he's graduated and he's been studying for

00:51:16.100 --> 00:51:19.040
the dental exams for those four years.

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:20.770
Hasn't actually gone to dental school yet.

00:51:20.770 --> 00:51:23.670
There are also some other patterns.

00:51:23.670 --> 00:51:27.510
And these are hilarious, actually.

00:51:27.510 --> 00:51:29.220
'Cause people ask, "Well, OK.

00:51:29.220 --> 00:51:30.270
So we could be solid blue.

00:51:30.270 --> 00:51:31.270
What does that mean?"

00:51:31.270 --> 00:51:33.220
What happens when a person holds a state that
was solid?

00:51:33.220 --> 00:51:34.780
And this doesn't happen all the time.

00:51:34.780 --> 00:51:38.830
But you can usually find it somewhere.

00:51:38.830 --> 00:51:40.190
And it's not just me, OK?

00:51:40.190 --> 00:51:41.780
This is in the literature.

00:51:41.780 --> 00:51:46.440
Watching television evokes almost no brain
activity in the neocortex.

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:47.930
I've seen two exceptions.

00:51:47.930 --> 00:51:52.720
And I did a whole like, very structured research
study with a student, with randomized introduction

00:51:52.720 --> 00:51:54.500
of film clips and so on.

00:51:54.500 --> 00:51:55.760
All very nicely done.

00:51:55.760 --> 00:51:57.650
The APA would love me for it.

00:51:57.650 --> 00:51:59.570
I did all the right things.

00:51:59.570 --> 00:52:00.570
Only two things.

00:52:00.570 --> 00:52:02.390
If you're familiar with the movie "Memento."

00:52:02.390 --> 00:52:06.880
So, the movie "Memento" follows a man who,
his short-term memory doesn't write itself

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:08.470
into long-term memory.

00:52:08.470 --> 00:52:14.790
And it's filmed in such a way that you experience
some of the same confusion that the character

00:52:14.790 --> 00:52:15.950
does.

00:52:15.950 --> 00:52:20.720
That evokes some brain activity.

00:52:20.720 --> 00:52:22.000
Everything else, from--.

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:27.390
Well, the other thing is there was an ending
scene in the first Charlie's Angels movie,

00:52:27.390 --> 00:52:33.240
which has each of four different protagonists,
each in a different location, fighting somebody

00:52:33.240 --> 00:52:37.220
different and we're just thrown as a viewer
into the middle of all of these different

00:52:37.220 --> 00:52:38.290
shots and cuts.

00:52:38.290 --> 00:52:41.850
So, it takes a while for the viewer to figure
out who's where and what is it that they're

00:52:41.850 --> 00:52:42.890
doing.

00:52:42.890 --> 00:52:50.380
All the other ten examples from Texas Chainsaw
Massacre to Teletubbies evoke no brain activity.

00:52:50.380 --> 00:52:55.250
So, what I tell parents "if you have a choice
between TV and video games, at least let your

00:52:55.250 --> 00:52:56.540
kids play video games."

00:52:56.540 --> 00:52:58.490
That's so much better than TV.

00:52:58.490 --> 00:52:59.920
Now, green.

00:52:59.920 --> 00:53:01.690
What happens when it's solid green?

00:53:01.690 --> 00:53:07.060
When they're doing speed dating and you dislike
someone, it's green.

00:53:07.060 --> 00:53:09.000
When a person is engaged in an argument.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:13.290
Now, if they get really active in the argument,
it might look like this, but a lot of the

00:53:13.290 --> 00:53:16.190
times it'll just have quite a bit of green.

00:53:16.190 --> 00:53:20.870
Losing at a game of cards.

00:53:20.870 --> 00:53:24.410
And I began to think about, OK, if these and
other situations, I said, "What did they all

00:53:24.410 --> 00:53:25.410
have in common?"

00:53:25.410 --> 00:53:27.100
And I would debrief them after the activity.

00:53:27.100 --> 00:53:30.760
It has a disassociation in common.

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:36.030
Disassociation means, in psychological terms,
that you don't want to feel your bodily sensations

00:53:36.030 --> 00:53:37.030
and your emotions.

00:53:37.030 --> 00:53:42.260
You want to separate yourself from what's
going on so that the cognition is separate

00:53:42.260 --> 00:53:45.920
from all those impulses and emotions that
might sway you.

00:53:45.920 --> 00:53:46.920
And it does make sense.

00:53:46.920 --> 00:53:50.790
I mean, if you don't like someone, you don't
want to feel the feeling of disliking them.

00:53:50.790 --> 00:53:52.211
How about losing at a card game?

00:53:52.211 --> 00:53:55.430
Anyone wanna dwell in that feeling of loss
and failure?

00:53:55.430 --> 00:53:56.910
No.

00:53:56.910 --> 00:53:58.420
Focus thinking though, also helps.

00:53:58.420 --> 00:54:00.460
