01:10:21.119 --> 01:10:22.119
That's relevant . Yes.

01:10:22.119 --> 01:10:25.190
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #7: You talked a little
bit about motivation as being one of the things

01:10:25.190 --> 01:10:28.809
that lights up at certain parts of the brain.

01:10:28.809 --> 01:10:33.810
Did you look at external motivation, or is
it just assuming an internal motivation?

01:10:33.810 --> 01:10:36.979
&gt;&gt;Dario Nardi: I do believe external motivation.

01:10:36.979 --> 01:10:37.979
Oh, right.

01:10:37.979 --> 01:10:38.979
Right.

01:10:38.979 --> 01:10:43.159
So, the question is, in terms of motivation
and competence , the sense of competence primarily

01:10:43.159 --> 01:10:44.679
comes from the inside.

01:10:44.679 --> 01:10:48.659
Motivation can come from the inside or there
can be peer pressure or social influence and

01:10:48.659 --> 01:10:51.340
guidance to help that come from the outside.

01:10:51.340 --> 01:10:57.340
There's a region back here, T5, which is really
strongly responsible for helping us respond

01:10:57.340 --> 01:10:59.739
to social feedback from others.

01:10:59.739 --> 01:11:03.909
And the more active that region was it seemed
like the more the person was driven to do

01:11:03.909 --> 01:11:09.250
behaviors based upon looks that they got from
other people, verbal feedback they got from

01:11:09.250 --> 01:11:10.250
others.

01:11:10.250 --> 01:11:13.580
In contrast, they had much more activity in
this region, which is actually diametrically

01:11:13.580 --> 01:11:14.580
opposite.

01:11:14.580 --> 01:11:18.389
So, this region here, but almost no activity
on this side.

01:11:18.389 --> 01:11:22.179
It seemed like no matter what we did, the
person might notice the feedback, but they

01:11:22.179 --> 01:11:24.459
have no interest in responding to it.

01:11:24.459 --> 01:11:32.690
In fact, it might even show some activity
here when they're curious what others are

01:11:32.690 --> 01:11:33.690
thinking.

01:11:33.690 --> 01:11:38.269
But once they hear the feedback, actually,
the activity goes away.

01:11:38.269 --> 01:11:39.850
And they don't respond to it.

01:11:39.850 --> 01:11:46.449
So, a good example is I'm in a fiction writing
group and there's a woman with INFP preferences.

01:11:46.449 --> 01:11:47.449
And I would predict.

01:11:47.449 --> 01:11:50.360
She would have a lot of activity here and
a little bit here.

01:11:50.360 --> 01:11:53.219
So, she's not really big on social feedback.

01:11:53.219 --> 01:11:57.110
And she brings her stories in and we give
her comments and she never incorporates the

01:11:57.110 --> 01:11:58.110
comments.

01:11:58.110 --> 01:12:00.600
But she's always asking for comments.

01:12:00.600 --> 01:12:02.540
And it's not just to be nice.

01:12:02.540 --> 01:12:07.630
And she said one time, she explained, "I'm
just trying to confirm what I think your feedback

01:12:07.630 --> 01:12:08.900
is going to be."

01:12:08.900 --> 01:12:14.739
But unless it's like a missing period or something,
she doesn't actually make the change.

01:12:14.739 --> 01:12:18.150
And so, that's an example where I think the
motivation in her case really comes from the

01:12:18.150 --> 01:12:19.310
inside.

01:12:19.310 --> 01:12:23.699
But for others, I've seen a couple of subjects
where it's just like, it's almost like they

01:12:23.699 --> 01:12:27.119
have like a hundred buttons on the outside
and you can just say or do things and they

01:12:27.119 --> 01:12:29.680
just like, keep following for the feedback
whatever you do.

01:12:29.680 --> 01:12:34.429
I mean, amazing sometimes, I think I'm not
even giving them feedback, but if I just glance

01:12:34.429 --> 01:12:36.360
this way, all of a sudden they like--.

01:12:36.360 --> 01:12:37.360
I had one kid.

01:12:37.360 --> 01:12:39.650
He had his feet on the table.

01:12:39.650 --> 01:12:40.909
And I didn't even turn my head.

01:12:40.909 --> 01:12:44.479
I just looked this way and I noticed it, and
I don't care actually.

01:12:44.479 --> 01:12:46.920
And all of a sudden he's like, "Oh, I have
to put my feet down and this and that."

01:12:46.920 --> 01:12:51.020
He was like hyper attentive to that external
feedback.

01:12:51.020 --> 01:12:52.020
Great question.

01:12:52.020 --> 01:12:53.020
Yes.

01:12:53.020 --> 01:12:57.079
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #8: Have you noticed
any cultural differences as you, with the

01:12:57.079 --> 01:12:58.079
subjects that you have?

01:12:58.079 --> 01:13:03.389
Like, people who are raised more with a language
system that's more symbolic as opposed to

01:13:03.389 --> 01:13:04.389
alphabetic?

01:13:04.389 --> 01:13:12.079
And how that's played into brain area reactions
[fades away]

01:13:12.079 --> 01:13:14.469
&gt;&gt;Dario Nardi: Great question.

01:13:14.469 --> 01:13:19.320
So, have I noticed some differences in brain
activity based upon cultural background?

01:13:19.320 --> 01:13:26.809
For example, if a person was raised learning
Kanji or the symbolic writing system as opposed

01:13:26.809 --> 01:13:32.150
to the simplified alphabetic system that we
use in English.

01:13:32.150 --> 01:13:33.150
The answer is yes.

01:13:33.150 --> 01:13:39.630
And in fact, I really wanted to explore cultural
differences, so I selected three, well, two

01:13:39.630 --> 01:13:43.179
primarily, but I would allow some other students
to come in, too.

01:13:43.179 --> 01:13:50.409
Japanese exchange students and students who
were first generation or Persian or Middle

01:13:50.409 --> 01:13:51.409
Eastern immigrant.

01:13:51.409 --> 01:13:56.440
So, mainly Persian, but there were some Lebanese
and so on.

01:13:56.440 --> 01:13:58.139
And tried to keep it to that.

01:13:58.139 --> 01:14:04.550
What I found was that in activities that are
more learned, for example, performing mathematics.

01:14:04.550 --> 01:14:05.550
And I would ask them--.

01:14:05.550 --> 01:14:09.940
They have an interview sheet as they come
in and I ask them to do some sample math problems

01:14:09.940 --> 01:14:11.210
and reflect on that.

01:14:11.210 --> 01:14:17.249
And let me know what kind of math methods,
if they remember, how is it that they learned

01:14:17.249 --> 01:14:18.289
math.

01:14:18.289 --> 01:14:22.499
And it was really fascinating to see the differences
in brain activity that reflected--.

01:14:22.499 --> 01:14:26.050
I could understand in terms of personality,
but this also seemed clearly related to the

01:14:26.050 --> 01:14:28.199
method that they learned with math.

01:14:28.199 --> 01:14:31.110
And a great example--the Japanese students.

01:14:31.110 --> 01:14:32.959
Incredibly efficient brain activity.

01:14:32.959 --> 01:14:33.959
And these were all students.

01:14:33.959 --> 01:14:36.980
I made sure to pick ones for the math when
I do the comparison that were all students

01:14:36.980 --> 01:14:40.099
who would use math as part of their majors.

01:14:40.099 --> 01:14:42.019
Incredibly efficient brain activity.

01:14:42.019 --> 01:14:46.770
Just like one perfect region, the P3 region,
which educators would hope would be like,

01:14:46.770 --> 01:14:54.159
the region for simpler mathematics as opposed
to over here, P4, for more spatial and multivariant

01:14:54.159 --> 01:14:55.709
mathematics.

01:14:55.709 --> 01:14:57.310
And no other regions really active.

01:14:57.310 --> 01:14:58.989
So, very fast, efficient.

01:14:58.989 --> 01:15:03.380
You wanna be using your brain at maximum capacity
when you're doing math problems if that's

01:15:03.380 --> 01:15:06.239
gonna be your job doing a lot it.

01:15:06.239 --> 01:15:08.320
In contrast, I had a student raised in--.

01:15:08.320 --> 01:15:15.350
A Middle Eastern student who had the French
method of learning math, which is a lot about

01:15:15.350 --> 01:15:16.690
sounding out and repeating.

01:15:16.690 --> 01:15:19.900
So, he showed a lot of auditory activity.

01:15:19.900 --> 01:15:25.360
The hassle is, though, the auditory areas
also keep track of their hearing in the physical

01:15:25.360 --> 01:15:27.010
environment.

01:15:27.010 --> 01:15:31.449
So he had difficulty doing the math problems
because there was noise in the environment.

01:15:31.449 --> 01:15:36.810
And he expressed he needed to work alone in
a really quiet space in order to do math.

01:15:36.810 --> 01:15:41.860
I had a student finally who came from Northern
California and learned in one of the new math

01:15:41.860 --> 01:15:46.310
systems where students are allowed to discover
principles for themselves and so on.

01:15:46.310 --> 01:15:48.829
And she worked quickly and she got all the
problems right.

01:15:48.829 --> 01:15:53.050
And she used well over half her brain to do
it.

01:15:53.050 --> 01:16:01.090
And unfortunately, the half that she used
didn't involve any of the key reasoning centers.

01:16:01.090 --> 01:16:02.090
And as she described it.

01:16:02.090 --> 01:16:04.670
She said, "I'm trying to remember what we
did and remember the formulas.

01:16:04.670 --> 01:16:09.550
And I know I was visualizing the problem and
then I was wondering if I was taking too long."

01:16:09.550 --> 01:16:13.050
And so, she ended up using everything that
would be part of an experiential process.

01:16:13.050 --> 01:16:17.229
And apparently, the new math methods for imparting
principles didn't actually impart any principles

01:16:17.229 --> 01:16:22.550
to her, which contradicted her personality
type preference, too.

01:16:22.550 --> 01:16:27.140
Which I thought, "Well, if it didn't work
for her, then what does that mean?"

01:16:27.140 --> 01:16:30.139
At least for the school that she attended
or to the teachers she had.

01:16:30.139 --> 01:16:32.199
So, it does seem there's some elements around
that.

01:16:32.199 --> 01:16:36.739
I also thought it was interesting when I compared
INFPs since I had seven of them and could

01:16:36.739 --> 01:16:38.280
look at their ethnic background.

01:16:38.280 --> 01:16:43.729
But the one who was the perfect listener--in
every situation, she was like, "What?

01:16:43.729 --> 01:16:44.729
You're talking?

01:16:44.729 --> 01:16:45.829
I'm gonna listen with my whole brain."

01:16:45.829 --> 01:16:48.790
Was the Japanese INFP.

01:16:48.790 --> 01:16:51.630
And I know, having lived in Japan and speaking
Japanese.

01:16:51.630 --> 01:16:52.820
It's really interesting with the grammar.

01:16:52.820 --> 01:16:56.900
You have to wait until the end of the sentence
to know what the verb is.

01:16:56.900 --> 01:16:58.709
And essentially, the most important part.

01:16:58.709 --> 01:17:01.650
So you really need to be a good listener in
Japanese.

01:17:01.650 --> 01:17:05.820
And then, she was female, which in Japanese
society would push it even further.

01:17:05.820 --> 01:17:07.030
She's a really great listener.

01:17:07.030 --> 01:17:10.750
INFP are already stereotyped as listeners
to begin with.

01:17:10.750 --> 01:17:12.349
And I'm expecting that from the brain activity.

01:17:12.349 --> 01:17:14.780
And she was like, super-listener.

01:17:14.780 --> 01:17:18.550
And just really listened to everyone actively.

01:17:18.550 --> 01:17:23.999
She might want to consider if she wants to
keep doing that all of her life.

01:17:23.999 --> 01:17:26.920
Now that she's learned this, it's up to her
what she does with that knowledge.

01:17:26.920 --> 01:17:33.829
Whereas, I had an INFP who was very, like,
European background, grew up in America and

01:17:33.829 --> 01:17:34.829
so on.

01:17:34.829 --> 01:17:36.460
And he did listening, but not nearly as much.

01:17:36.460 --> 01:17:40.039
And those are specific students, but if I
put them all along a spectrum I can see that

01:17:40.039 --> 01:17:46.260
there's definitely, where the Persian INFP
probably did the least listening of the seven

01:17:46.260 --> 01:17:47.539
that were there.

01:17:47.539 --> 01:17:48.539
Yeah.

01:17:48.539 --> 01:17:49.539
Yes.

01:17:49.539 --> 01:17:54.190
&gt;&gt;FEMALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #9: I was wondering
about something that you said earlier.

01:17:54.190 --> 01:17:58.719
I was wondering in a lot of what you described
as correlation of these personality types

01:17:58.719 --> 01:18:05.659
to brain activity, is there anything that
you would suggest is translatable to our lives

01:18:05.659 --> 01:18:07.880
in terms of how to cause changes?

01:18:07.880 --> 01:18:11.199
For example, how one personality type, how
would that interact with another or might

01:18:11.199 --> 01:18:21.479
become a better listener by engaging brain
activity in a neighboring region or something

01:18:21.479 --> 01:18:22.479
like that?

01:18:22.479 --> 01:18:26.229
&gt;&gt;Dario Nardi: So, the question is, are there
ways to take this information we've learned

01:18:26.229 --> 01:18:31.309
about the brain and translate into practical
applications in our everyday lives?

01:18:31.309 --> 01:18:36.579
And some examples would be having a better
idea of how to interact with somebody else.

01:18:36.579 --> 01:18:43.540
Can we actually improve, perhaps, a particular
ability or develop particular skill around

01:18:43.540 --> 01:18:44.540
something.

01:18:44.540 --> 01:18:47.219
I can think of three options right off.

01:18:47.219 --> 01:18:52.790
One is that you go to Australia and you do
their trans cranial stimulation.

01:18:52.790 --> 01:18:53.790
You participate in that.

01:18:53.790 --> 01:18:57.940
So, they turn off certain regions of the brain
by stimulating them or turn on other regions.

01:18:57.940 --> 01:19:02.079
And they've really had some nice success in
terms of shifting people's activity.

01:19:02.079 --> 01:19:05.579
Many of us, apparently, are really good artists
and we don't know it.

01:19:05.579 --> 01:19:10.829
And the trick is to actually turn off regions
in the left frontal areas and especially in

01:19:10.829 --> 01:19:12.460
this region right around here.

01:19:12.460 --> 01:19:15.909
And all of a sudden, for two or three or maybe
four hours, we're gonna have significantly

01:19:15.909 --> 01:19:17.929
better drawing ability.

01:19:17.929 --> 01:19:21.210
Because apparently, there are signals from
here that are sent out to block signals from

01:19:21.210 --> 01:19:22.340
the other hemisphere.

01:19:22.340 --> 01:19:25.170
So, that's an example where we've seen some
nice stuff.

01:19:25.170 --> 01:19:29.139
That's a very high-tech end, but maybe Google
could arrange that for you.

01:19:29.139 --> 01:19:30.219
[laughter]

01:19:30.219 --> 01:19:33.909
Another is that after this session there's
a break.

01:19:33.909 --> 01:19:39.550
And then there's a human resources, another
hour and a half activity workshop.

01:19:39.550 --> 01:19:43.909
And that's when we'll talk about actually
what are those coaching tips and techniques

01:19:43.909 --> 01:19:44.959
for those eight types.

01:19:44.959 --> 01:19:46.590
And there really are a lot that come out of
it.

01:19:46.590 --> 01:19:47.849
Much more than I've--.

01:19:47.849 --> 01:19:52.410
I mentioned personality types without saying
for this for this for that for that.

01:19:52.410 --> 01:19:56.929
'Cause personality type, we would say, some
colleagues have asked me, "OK, now that you've

01:19:56.929 --> 01:20:01.540
gotten this point, isn't personality type
like Myers-Briggs just nice scaffolding to

01:20:01.540 --> 01:20:02.540
problem-solving?

01:20:02.540 --> 01:20:05.170
And now that you figured out what the brain
does, you can throw it away."

01:20:05.170 --> 01:20:06.219
And I said, "No."

01:20:06.219 --> 01:20:07.810
Because I'm not done yet.

01:20:07.810 --> 01:20:11.969
And also, most of the time we really don't
know what's going on inside a person's brain.

01:20:11.969 --> 01:20:17.300
And it turns out to be pretty good if we also
know the person's expertise skill sets.

01:20:17.300 --> 01:20:22.869
Those two pieces of information together can
give us a pretty good picture of what's likely

01:20:22.869 --> 01:20:23.979
to go on.

01:20:23.979 --> 01:20:26.840
And then from there, we can actually do some
interactive things.

01:20:26.840 --> 01:20:31.079
We can say maybe this is the kind of person
